claims:
Claims 1. A method for in-line detection of at least one chemical compound in beer, comprising: pumping a wort sample, by a pump that increases pressure on the wort sample, from a fermentation vessel into a heater; ramping, by the heater, a temperature of the wort sample up from a starting temperature to a decomposition temperature, then back down to the starting temperature; passing the wort sample from the heater to an infrared (IR) cell; measuring, by the IR cell, an amount of the at least one chemical compound in the wort sample by IR spectroscopy; comparing, by a controller, signals from the IR cell when the heater is off and when the heater is on to determine a concentration of the at least one chemical compound in the wort sample; passing the wort sample to a check valve to eliminate back flow and prevent degassing the wort sample; and returning the wort sample to the fermentation vessel. 2. The method of claim 1, wherein the at least one chemical compound comprises at least one of a-acetolactate, carbon dioxide, a-acetohydroxybutyrate, and a vicinal diketone. 3. The method of claim 1, wherein the heater is a Peltier heater. 4. The method of claim 1, wherein the IR cell is an IR attenuated total reflectance (IR-ATR) cell, wherein the IR-ATR cell utilizes at least one of RAMAN spectroscopy, gas electrode analysis, headspace analysis by gas chromatography, and electrochemical detection in the measuring step. 5. A system for in-line detection of at least one chemical compound in beer, comprising: a pump, configured to pump a wort sample from a fermentation vessel and increase the pressure on the wort sample; a heater, configured to receive the wort sample from the pump and ramp a temperature of the wort sample up from a starting temperature to a decomposition temperature, then back down to the starting temperature; 

 an infrared (IR) cell, configured to measure an amount of the at least one chemical compound in the wort sample by IR spectroscopy; a controller, configured to compare signals from the IR cell when the heater is off and when the heater is on to determine a concentration of the at least one chemical compound in the wort sample; and a check valve, configured to eliminate back flow and prevent degassing the wort sample. 6. The system of claim 5, wherein the at least one chemical compound comprises at least one of a-acetolactate, carbon dioxide, a-acetohydroxybutyrate, and a vicinal diketone. 7. The system of claim 5, wherein the heater is a Peltier heater. 8. The system of claim 5, wherein the IR cell is an IR attenuated total reflectance (IR-ATR) cell, wherein the IR-ATR cell is configured to utilize at least one of RAMAN spectroscopy, gas electrode analysis, headspace analysis by gas chromatography, and electrochemical detection. 9. A method for controlling the quantity of at least one chemical compound in a beer brewing process, comprising the steps of: a) providing a system comprising: a heater; an infrared (IR) cell, in fluid communication with the heater; and a controller, interconnected to the pump, the heater, the IR cell, and a fermentation vessel; b) removing a wort sample from the fermentation vessel; c) measuring a first carbon dioxide concentration in the wort sample; d) heating the wort sample to a target temperature; e) obtaining spectroscopy data for the wort sample by IR spectroscopy; f) interpreting the spectroscopy data according to the first carbon dioxide concentration and a first algorithm to determine a second carbon dioxide concentration in the wort sample; g) calculating a concentration of the at least one chemical compound in the wort sample according to the second carbon dioxide concentration and a second algorithm; h) returning the wort sample to the fermentation vessel; and 

 i) modifying at least one fermentation parameter of the beer brewing process according to the concentration of the at least one chemical compound and a third algorithm. 10. The method of claim 9, wherein the method is completed in a time of between about 30 seconds and about 6 minutes. 11. The method of claim 10, wherein the method is completed in a time of between about 2 minutes and about 3 minutes. 12. The method of claim 9, wherein the at least one chemical compound comprises at least one of a-acetolactate (AAL), carbon dioxide, a-acetohydroxybutyrate, and a vicinal diketone (VDKs). 13. The method of claim 9, wherein the heater is a Peltier heater. 14. The method of claim 9, wherein the at least one fermentation parameter comprises at least one of a fermentation time and a fermentation temperature. 15. The method of claim 9, wherein the IR cell is an IR attenuated total reflectance (IR- ATR) cell . 16. The method of claim 9, wherein light emitted by and reflected in the IR-ATR cell may have an emitted wavelength of between about 1 micron and about 100 microns. 17. The method of claim 9, wherein the wort sample has at least one of a mass of between about 0.01 g and about 0.5 g and a volume of between about 0.01 mL and about 0.5 mL. 18. The method of claim 9, wherein the target temperature is sufficient to rapidly convert substantially all AAL in the wort sample to VDKs and carbon dioxide. 19. The method of claim 18, wherein the target temperature is between about 50 Â°C and about 110 Â°C. 20. The method of claim 18, wherein the target temperature is at least about 35 Â°C.
